 two children together, Tabbran, and Taurieal.  The boys were born very close together (about 20 years), which is very rare for elf families, but Tabbran's parents saw it as a blessing.  Vigorously overprotective of their sons, the children were destined to follow the life of the merchant, and stay wealthy, than risk the dangers of adventure.  But as is apt to happen to wealthy children who are bored, they begin to get into mischief.  <br><br>One day, Tabbran's mischief took him a bit too far.  He traveled to the highest point in Kelethin, hoping to throw fishing grubs down on the unsuspecting people who are training in the fields below.  But what he accidentally found was the Rogue's guild after a particularly large take.  Obviously not expecting a mischievous young elf to walk right into their business dealings, there was rather loose security, which Tabbran bypassed, or so he thought.<br><br>Taking a bauble or two, and hoping to get away with it, the elfling tried to escape, but was caught red-handed.  Expin, the leader of the Scouts of Tunare had caught him fairly, and dangled the little elf over the edge of the platform.  It was then that a deal was struck between the Scouts and Tabbran, he would become one of them (Expin saw that he had promise) and they would let him live.  It was then that he was inducted as a Martyr of Tunare, the true name that the Scouts held private to themselves.<br><br>He began his training with the Scouts shortly thereafter, and when he felt that he had advanced sufficently in thier ways, he announced to his father that he wished to become an adventurer and go to see the world.  His parents and him fought over this point for hours with neither side gaining any headway, until he played his trump card, and threw down an old, and much used sword, at his father's feet.<br><br>The sword actually belonged to his mother, but the point was delivered.  His parents were adventurers in their past, and forbidding him from seeing the world was simply unfair.  His father conceded the point finally, and gave him reluctant permission to leave and become an adventurer of the lands.  Ever the tagalong, Taurieal wished to follow in his older brother's footsteps.  And the cycle began again.<br><br>Religion:<br><br>There was room only for one Goddess in the Kythrandraal household, and that was Tunare.  Both sons worship the Goddess of Nature, Tabbran particularly so.  Being a Martyr of Tunare holds special meaning to him, and he intends to hold up his end of the bargain that spared his life until the day he can no longer do so.<br><br>Personality:<br><br>Honing his skills to perfection has ever been a priority for Tabbran, he's always seeking to push himself to the next edge, walking the razor thin line that separates success from disaster.  He plays this all off by having a nonchalance about him, a casual uncaring attitude that eases pressure in whatever trouble he got himself into this time.  He's generous with his family, bringing back many treasures obtained on his travelling across the world and moon, and regularly gets into disputes with his father and mother over his chosen profession (They don't care that he's a Rogue, they care that he's an adventuruer).<br><br>Ultimately, Tabbran sees himself as an instrument of his Goddess.  Through and through he is a Martyr of Tunare, he feels that the Martyrs are closer to Tunare than even the Soldiers of Tunare (the Druids), and does the bidding of his Goddess that is best left unspoken. <p><font size=4><font color=666666>T</font><font color=000066>abbran </font><font color=666666>K</font><font color=000066>ythrandraal</font></font><b><HR width=38.5%>           </hr></b><b>Scourge of Oggok</b><BR>Martyr of Tunare, Murderer for the Mother<BR><i>I'm sure I'll find you were as evil as me.</i></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#f7f7f7><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub95.ezboard.com/udldragonbreath.sh